A helper function for concatenating vectors.

This function concatenates two vectors having the same element type. If the second vector has fewer elements than the first, it is padded with undefs.

<Link id="l00605" /><CodeLine lineNumber="605"><Highlight kind="normal">      SingleInputAction(&#42;It, SrcReg, <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/support/md5-cpp/#ac0eafdc9ee161b71e7af98af736952fd">I</a>);</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00608" /><CodeLine lineNumber="608"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">default</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">: &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00835" /><CodeLine lineNumber="835"><Highlight kind="normal">      </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// If any of M&#39;s operands demand more bits than MinBW then M cannot be</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00836" /><CodeLine lineNumber="836"><Highlight kind="normal">      </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// performed safely in MinBW.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00837" /><CodeLine lineNumber="837"><Highlight kind="normal">      </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">if</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (<a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/#a61d13d6824ec46c31260a4fd0997eda0">any&#95;of</a>(<a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/codegen/lib/codegen/globalisel/irtranslator-cpp/#abe44dfdea65b4f7e11e0a608ab708b76">MI</a>-&gt;operands(), &#91;&amp;DB, MinBW&#93;(<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/use">Use</a> &amp;U) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00839" /><CodeLine lineNumber="839"><Highlight kind="normal">            </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// For constants shift amounts, check if the shift would result in</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00840" /><CodeLine lineNumber="840"><Highlight kind="normal">            </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// poison.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00847" /><CodeLine lineNumber="847"><Highlight kind="normal">          &#125;))</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01266" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1266"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01267" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1267"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Analyze interleaved accesses and collect them into interleaved load and</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01268" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1268"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// store groups.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01269" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1269"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1270"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// When generating code for an interleaved load group, we effectively hoist all</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1271"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// loads in the group to the location of the first load in program order. When</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1272"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// generating code for an interleaved store group, we sink all stores to the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1273"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// location of the last store. This code motion can change the order of load</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1274"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// and store instructions and may break dependences.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1275"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1276"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The code generation strategy mentioned above ensures that we won&#39;t violate</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1277"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// any write-after-read (WAR) dependences.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1278"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1279"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// E.g., for the WAR dependence:  a = A&#91;i&#93;;      // (1)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1280"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//                                A&#91;i&#93; = b;      // (2)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01281" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1281"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01282" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1282"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The store group of (2) is always inserted at or below (2), and the load</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1283"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// group of (1) is always inserted at or above (1). Thus, the instructions will</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1284"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// never be reordered. All other dependences are checked to ensure the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1285"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// correctness of the instruction reordering.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1286"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1287"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The algorithm visits all memory accesses in the loop in bottom-up program</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01288" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1288"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// order. Program order is established by traversing the blocks in the loop in</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01289" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1289"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// reverse postorder when collecting the accesses.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1290"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1291"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// We visit the memory accesses in bottom-up order because it can simplify the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01292" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1292"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// construction of store groups in the presence of write-after-write (WAW)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01293" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1293"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// dependences.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01294" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1294"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01295" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1295"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// E.g., for the WAW dependence:  A&#91;i&#93; = a;      // (1)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01296" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1296"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//                                A&#91;i&#93; = b;      // (2)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01297" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1297"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//                                A&#91;i + 1&#93; = c;  // (3)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01298" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1298"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01299" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1299"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// We will first create a store group with (3) and (2). (1) can&#39;t be added to</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01300" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1300"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// this group because it and (2) are dependent. However, (1) can be grouped</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01301" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1301"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// with other accesses that may precede it in program order. Note that a</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01302" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1302"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// bottom-up order does not imply that WAW dependences should not be checked.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01303" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1303" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/interleavedaccessinfo/#af587d7218fa15a456103c3d2125a1fc8"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/interleavedaccessinfo/#af587d7218fa15a456103c3d2125a1fc8">InterleavedAccessInfo::analyzeInterleaving</a>(</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01325" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1325"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Search in bottom-up program order for pairs of accesses (A and B) that can</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01326" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1326"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// form interleaved load or store groups. In the algorithm below, access A</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01327" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1327"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// precedes access B in program order. We initialize a group for B in the</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01328" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1328"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// outer loop of the algorithm, and then in the inner loop, we attempt to</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01329" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1329"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// insert each A into B&#39;s group if:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01330" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1330"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01331" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1331"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  1 A and B have the same stride,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01332" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1332"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  2 A and B have the same memory object size, and</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01333" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1333"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  3 A belongs in B&#39;s group according to its distance from B.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01334" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1334"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01335" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1335"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Special care is taken to ensure group formation will not break any</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01336" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1336"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// dependences.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01337" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1337"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">for</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">auto</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> BI = AccessStrideInfo.<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mapvector/#afa84f2e649eac2b43ff8e4a5e3d866e8">rbegin</a>(), E = AccessStrideInfo.<a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/mapvector/#a290c99a05ce4f33c242f41f0a1d59b84">rend</a>();</Highlight></CodeLine>
